<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911120-0051</DOCNO><DOCID>911120-0051.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Convex Computer Corp.:   Texas Company Introduces   Mini-Supercomputer System</HL><DATE>11/20/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   CNX</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)</IN><NS>NEW PRODUCTS andamp; SERVICES (PDT)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Convex Computer Corp., Richardson, Texas, said itintroduced an entry-level mini-supercomputer system aimed atsites where space and power supplies are limited.   The system, the C3400-ES, uses less than half the space ofa standard C3400 system, meaning the new system could be usedon ships, submarines and trucks. The computer comes witheither one or two central processors and stores up to ahalf-gigabyte, or about 500 million characters. The C3400systems can come with as many as eight central processors andfour gigabytes of storage.</LP><TEXT>   Convex, a supercomputer maker, said the new system's pricewill start at $295,000, compared with the $495,000 beginningprice for the standard C3400 system. Although the company hasa less advanced group of computers, the C3200 series, thosecomputers are marketed for use as data managers and fileservers, while the C3400ES will be targeted for computingfunctions, the company said.</TEXT></DOC>